# TypeScript Best Practices

## Type System

- Prefer types over interfaces for object definitions
- Use union/intersection/mapped types appropriately
- Avoid `any`; prefer `unknown` and precise narrowing
- Avoid enums; use maps or union literals
- Use generics for reusable patterns

## Naming & Conventions

- Use PascalCase for type names
- Use camelCase for variables and functions
- Use UPPER_CASE for constants
- Use descriptive names with auxiliary verbs (`isLoading`, `hasError`)

## Organization

- Keep type definitions close to usage; co-locate component props
- Do not create barrel files via `index.ts` for exports
- Place shared types in a dedicated `types` directory when necessary

## Functions & Errors

- Provide explicit return types for public functions
- Prefer arrow functions; use early returns to reduce nesting
- Implement typed error handling and custom error types
- Prefer async/await; handle rejections with typed catches

## Patterns & Utilities

- Use discriminated unions for complex state
- Implement type predicates for narrowing
- Prefer `Record<K, T>` over `{ [key: K]: T }`
- Use `satisfies` to validate config objects while preserving literals
- Use branded types for type-safe identifiers
- Prefer `??` and `?.` for defaults and optionals

## React-Specific Types

- Do not import the global React namespace
- Do not type components as `FC<Props>`
- For HTML-wrapping components without refs, use `ComponentPropsWithoutRef<T>`
- For HTML-wrapping components with refs, use `ComponentPropsWithRef<T>`
- For non-HTML components that accept children, use `PropsWithChildren<T>`
